					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Ron Carlson&#8217;s New Novel to Hit Bookshelves This Summer</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 3-25-09</p>
			
			
							<p>Utah native Ron Carlson is one of my favorite short story writers&#8212;his humor and insights are always sharp, his plots are engaging, and his characters convincing.&nbsp; His stories are often set amid dynamic Western landscapes that he describes expertly.&nbsp; Lately Carlson has been taking a break from short stories, however, to continue his career as a novelist.&nbsp; He published two novels early on, 1977&#8217;s <I>Betrayed by F. Scott Fitzgerald</I> and 1981&#8217;s <I>Truants</I> before switching his focus to stories for over two decades.&nbsp; In 2003 he published a young adult novel, <I>The Speed of Light</I>, and two years ago he came out with his first novel for adults in 26 years, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/index.php/city/article/mountain_men_ron_carlsons_five_skies/C104/L104/" title="Five Skies">Five Skies</a></I>.&nbsp; When <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_ron_carlson/C39/L39/" title="I interviewed him about that book">I interviewed him about that book</a>, he said he couldn&#8217;t explain why he recently decided to shift back to writing novels:
</p>
<p>
&#8220;I&#8217;ve written a number of stories in the past two years,&#8221; Carlson said, &#8220;but I am writing novels.&nbsp; I can&#8217;t say why.&nbsp; Something happened to me, my desire to sustain these dreams.&nbsp; The pleasures and challenges of the longer form have my attention now.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
The folks at the <a target="_blank" href="http://wyomingarts.blogspot.com/2009/03/carlsons-latest-novel-set-in-wind.html" title="Wyoming Arts Blog">Wyoming Arts Blog</a> recently noted that Carlson&#8217;s new novel, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780670021000,00.html?strSrchSql=signal+ron+carlson/The_Signal_Ron_Carlson" title="The Signal">The Signal</a></I> (Viking, $25.95) is due out in June, and that it will be set in Wyoming&#8217;s Wind River Range.&nbsp; The book received a starred review in Publisher&#8217;s Weekly (that means they considered it extra good).&nbsp; The PW reviewer writes; &#8220;The dense Wind River Mountains of western Wyoming is where Carlson (<I>Five Skies</I>) sets his brooding latest, a tale of expired love and desperate measures&#8230;Carlson has produced a work of masterful fiction, combining the sad inevitability of a doomed relationship with sheer nail-biting suspense.&#8221;  It sounds like it will be a great read for the summer.
</p>
<p>
The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.denverpost.com/search/ci_11962685" title="Denver Post reported">Denver Post reported</a> that Thomas G. Andrews, an assistant history professor at the University of Colorado at Denver, will receive the $10,000 Bancroft Prize from Columbia University for his 2008 book <i>Killing for Coal: America&#8217;s Deadliest Labor War</i>.&nbsp; The award is given for books of &#8220;exceptional merit in the fields of American history, biography and diplomacy,&#8221; and Andrews shares the award with two other writers, Drew Gilpin Faust for <i>This Republic of Suffering: Death and the American Civil War</i> and Pekka H&#228;m&#228;l&#228;inen for <i>The Comanche Empire</i>.&nbsp; Andrews told the Post, &#8220;I never really thought I would ever achieve this,&#8221; Andrews said. &#8220;I&#8217;m still waiting for someone to call me and tell me it&#8217;s an elaborate practical joke.&#8221;   Watch for our review of the book in the coming weeks. 
</p>
<p>
Christian Martin wrote in to mention several events going on at the North Cascades Environmental Learning Center in the coming months.&nbsp; In April, well-known librarian Nancy Pearl (author of <i>Book Lust</i>) will lead the<a target="_blank" href="http://www.ncascades.org/programs/seminars/course.html?workshop_id=941" title=" Booklovers Weekend"> Booklovers Weekend</a> and Nick O&#8217;Connel will lead a <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ncascades.org/programs/seminars/course.html?workshop_id=941" title="Writing About the Outdoors ">Writing About the Outdoors </a>seminar.&nbsp; Rick Bass will join several other regional writers in leading a <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ncascades.org/programs/seminars/course.html?workshop_id=970" title="four-day workshop ">four-day workshop </a>there from July 30 through August 2.&nbsp; A series of events will explore the legacy of the Beat Poets, including three who served as fire lookouts in the North Cascades--Jack Kerouac, Gary Snyder, and Philip Whalen. A <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ncascades.org/programs/seminars/course.html?workshop_id=976" title="seminar">seminar</a> on the topic is scheduled for August, and poet <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ncascades.org/get_outside/events/snyder.html" title="Gary Snyder">Gary Snyder</a> will appear on May 27.
</p>
<p>
The talented Oregon writer <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_molly_gloss/C39/L39/" title="Molly Gloss">Molly Gloss</a>&#8216;s latest novel, <i><a target="_blank" href="http://www.mollygloss.com/hearts.html" title="The Hearts of Horses">The Hearts of Horses</a></i>, is out now in paperback, and Gloss has been <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mollygloss.com/app.html" title="visiting bookstores across Oregon and Washington">visiting bookstores across Oregon and Washington</a> this month, participating in the One Community, One Book events in Longview, Washington, and several &#8220;Celebrate Oregon Writers&#8221; events.&nbsp; Catch her this weekend at Book People in Moscow, Idaho on March 28 (12-2 p.m.).&nbsp; Another reading of interest there is on April 2 (5-7 p.m.), when Alan Weltzien will present <i>The Norman MacLean Reader</i>.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional book news and events to share?&nbsp; <script type="text/javascript">
